Yes, I have experience working in both product and service environments, and both have their own advantages.

In a product-based company, you usually work on the same product for a longer time, so you get deeper ownership of the system and can focus more on improving the product, optimizing performance, and building long-term features.

In a service-based company, you get exposure to different projects and industries, which helps you learn new technologies and understand different business requirements. It also gives opportunities to work with diverse teams and sometimes interact with clients directly.

I think both environments help developers grow in different ways, and the key is adapting and contributing effectively to whichever environment you are in.

